  "prompt": "Why are birth rates lower in developed countries?",
  "response": "Birth rates in developed countries tend to be lower for several interrelated reasons:\n\n1. **Economic Factors**: In developed nations, the cost of raising children is significantly higher. Parents often face expenses related to housing, education, healthcare, and childcare, which can deter larger families.\n\n2. **Education and Career**: Higher levels of education, particularly among women, often lead to career prioritization and a delay in childbirth. Many women choose to invest time in education and career development before starting families.\n\n3. **Access to Family Planning**: Developed countries typically provide better access to contraception and family planning services, allowing couples greater control over the number and timing of children.\n\n4. **Cultural Shifts**: Social norms regarding family size have shifted in many developed countries. There is often less societal pressure to have large families, and smaller families may be viewed as more ideal.\n\n5. **Work-Life Balance Challenges**: The demands of modern work life, including long hours and job instability, can make raising children seem daunting. Many parents may choose to postpone or limit having children due to these pressures.\n\n6. **Urbanization**: As more people move to urban areas, where living space is often limited and costly, the practicality of having larger families decreases.\n\n7. **Changing Values**: Changing life priorities, such as a focus on personal fulfillment, travel, and experiences over traditional family structures, can lead to lower birth rates.\n\n8. **Delayed Marriage**: In many developed countries, people are marrying later in life, which naturally leads to fewer children due to the biological window for childbearing.\n\nThese factors interact in complex ways, contributing to the overall trend of lower birth rates in developed nations.",
